SIMPLE: sinister
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sinister
<hw>Sin"is*ter</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧n"⟦icr⟧s*t⟦etil⟧r; 277)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <note>[Accented on the middle syllable by the older poets,
as Shakespeare, Milton, Dryden.]</note> <ety>[L. <ets>sinister</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>sinistre</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>On the left hand, or
the side of the left hand; left; -- opposed to <ant>dexter</ant>, or
<ant>right</ant>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Here on his <xex>sinister</xex>
cheek.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My mother's blood⟦br⟧
Runs on the dexter cheek, and this <qex>sinister</qex>⟦br⟧
Bounds in my father's</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In heraldy the <xex>sinister</xex> side of an escutcheon
is the side which would be on the left of the bearer of the shield, and
opposite the right hand of the beholder.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unlucky; inauspicious; disastrous; injurious; evil;
-- the left being usually regarded as the unlucky side; <as>as,
<ex>sinister</ex> influences</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the several ills that visit earth,⟦br⟧
Brought forth by night, with a <qex>sinister</qex> birth.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wrong, as springing from indirection or obliquity;
perverse; dishonest; corrupt; <as>as, <ex>sinister</ex>
aims</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nimble and <qex>sinister</qex> tricks and shifts.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He scorns to undermine another's interest by any
<qex>sinister</qex> or inferior arts.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He read in their looks . . . <qex>sinister</qex> intentions
directed particularly toward himself.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Indicative of lurking evil or harm; boding covert
danger; <as>as, a <ex>sinister</ex> countenance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bar sinister</b></col>. <fld>(Her.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Bar</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Sinister aspect</b></col>
<fld>(Astrol.)</fld>, <cd>an appearance of two planets happening
according to the succession of the signs, as Saturn in Aries, and Mars
in the same degree of Gemini.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Sinister
base</b></col>, <col><b>Sinister chief</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under
<er>Escutcheon</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sinister-handed</ent>⟦br⟧
